Produced by Cukie Dady, “Lala” is a soulful of Bongo Fleva and soft Afro-pop, built around a tender theme of intimacy, emotional vulnerability, and timeless love. Harmonize pours his heart out as he sings about finally falling deeply in love expressing joy he’s never felt before and a desire to spend forever with his partner. His words, “You smell like honey, you're the only one,” paint a vivid picture of romantic admiration.

Abigail Chams responds with heartfelt emotion, sharing the internal conflict of trying to resist love but ultimately surrendering to it. Her vocals are soft yet striking as she confesses, “Why ghafla nakuita honey hivi mapenzi kitu gani, I don’t know why.” There’s a sense of honesty and youthful vulnerability in her delivery, making the record even more relatable.

The chorus, “Kifuani lalaa usinzie” (Lay on my chest, Fall asleep), becomes a comforting refrain a symbolic invitation into a safe space of love, peace, and emotional connection.

With unmatched chemistry and heartfelt storytelling, Harmonize and Abigail Chams once again deliver a song that resonates deeply. “Lala” is not just a duet it's a musical embrace that reminds listeners of the beauty of finding love, and the comfort of being seen, heard, and held.

After a string of successful collaborations, Tanzanian superstars Harmonize and Abigail Chams reunite for a deeply emotional and melodically rich new single titled “Lala.” This marks their fourth joint project, following fan-favorites “Closer,” “Leave Me Alone,” and “Me Too.”

Produced by Cukie Dady, “Lala” is a soulful of Bongo Fleva and soft Afro-pop, built around a tender theme of intimacy, emotional vulnerability, and timeless love. Harmonize pours his heart out as he sings about finally falling deeply in love expressing joy he’s never felt before and a desire to spend forever with his partner. His words, “You smell like honey, you're the only one,” paint a vivid picture of romantic admiration.

Abigail Chams responds with heartfelt emotion, sharing the internal conflict of trying to resist love but ultimately surrendering to it. Her vocals are soft yet striking as she confesses, “Why ghafla nakuita honey hivi mapenzi kitu gani, I don’t know why.” There’s a sense of honesty and youthful vulnerability in her delivery, making the record even more relatable.

The chorus, “Kifuani lalaa usinzie” (Lay on my chest, Fall asleep), becomes a comforting refrain a symbolic invitation into a safe space of love, peace, and emotional connection.

With unmatched chemistry and heartfelt storytelling, Harmonize and Abigail Chams once again deliver a song that resonates deeply. “Lala” is not just a duet it's a musical embrace that reminds listeners of the beauty of finding love, and the comfort of being seen, heard, and held.
